  <static seed="1464" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations70.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{x-4}{x-7}+\frac{3}{x-3}} = -1 }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{6,1\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of fractions, we multiply each term in this equation by the common denominator, which is <m>{\left(x-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}</m> in this example.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp {\frac{x-4}{x-7}+\frac{3}{x-3}} = -1 \\
   \amp {\frac{x-4}{x-7}\mathopen{}\left(x-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)+\frac{3}{x-3}\mathopen{}\left(x-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)} ={-\left(x-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)} \\
   \amp {\left(x-4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)+3\mathopen{}\left(x-7\right)} = {-\left(x^{2}-10x+21\right)} \\
   \amp {x^{2}-7x+12+3x-21} = {10x-x^{2}-21} \\
   \amp {x^{2}-4x-9} = {10x-x^{2}-21} \\
   \amp {x^{2}-4x-9+x^{2}-10x+21} = 0 \\
   \amp {2x^{2}-14x+12} = 0 \\
   \amp {2\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}-7x+6\right)} = 0 \\
   \amp {2\mathopen{}\left(x-6\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-1\right)} = 0 \\
   \amp {x-6}=0 \:\: or\:\: {x-1}=0 \\
   \amp x=6 \:\: or\:\: x=1
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p><alert>Checking</alert></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp x - 7 = 0 \amp \;\amp  x - 3=0 \\
   \amp x=7 \amp \;\amp  x=3
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>7</m> and <m>3</m> from the solution set, so the final solution is <m>x=6</m> and <m>x=1</m>.</p>
</solution>
